<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
    <head>
        <title>Cheat Sheet</title>
        
        <!--This is a Cheat Sheet-->
    </head>
<header><h1>The official Cheat Sheet</h1>
</header>   
<body>
<article>
    <p>Here is a list of cheats for html semantics!
</p>
<p>Remember that the semantic html elements to not actually do anything functional for you html code. However they make the reading easier for both the computer and people who might wanna read the actual code</p></article>
<table class="table1" class="center">
    <tr>
      <th class="intro" colspan="2">HTML Section Cheats</th>
      </tr>
      <tr>
      <th>&lt;header&gt;</th>
      <td>Here you can include the introductory information like h1. </td> 
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <th>&lt;article&gt;</th>
      <td>The article is an independent self contained content. </td> 
      </tr>
      <tr> 
        <th>&lt;section&gt;</th>
        <td>The section element defines a section in a document, like for example a chapter.</td>
      </tr>
     <tr>
       <th>&lt;aside&gt;</th>
<td>The aside element defines information thats aside from the content it's placed in, like a sidebar</td>
     </tr>
    <tr>
      <th>&lt;footer&gt;</th>
      <td>The footer element defines the footer for a docuement or section</td> 
    </tr>
  </table>
  <table class="table2" class="center">
    <tr>
<th class="intro" colspan="2">CSS rules and information for semantic HTML</th>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td>The css that is used for the semantic html element will affect the output as any other html element.</td>
  <td>Remember to link your css and have it connected to your html index file</td>
</tr>
  </table>


  <table class="table3" class="center">
    <tr>
      <th class="intro" colspan="2">Table elements</th>
      </tr>
      <tr>
      <td>&lt;tr&gt;</td>
      <td>the tr stands for table row and adds a new row to your table</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>&lt;td&gt;</td>
        <td>The td stands for table data and adds info at your table row</td>
      </tr>
      </table>
      <table class="table4">
          <th class="intro" colspan="2">There is also lots of tags that help us browse the html code</th>
         </tr>
        <tr>
        <td>&lt;thead&gt;</td>
        <td>The thead tag is used to group header content in an html table</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>&lt;tbody&gt;</td>
        <td>The tbody is a html tag that is used to group the body content in an HTML table</td>
      </tr>
</table>
</body>
